Here's the context document for `docs/STATUS.md`:

Living project-management artifact — a prioritized backlog table, not source code. Tracks pending work items across the ctx-* toolchain (context generation, verification, summarization, hook integration) with columns for task, description, impact, and difficulty, sorted by impact then difficulty.

Points to `docs/DECISIONS.md` for architectural rationale (ADR-style decision log referenced by number, e.g. ADR-054, ADR-039, ADR-020, ADR-049) and instructs readers to run `ctx-context .` to derive current architecture rather than trusting any static description here.

Non-obvious behavior: entries reference specific line numbers and function names in the actual codebase (e.g. `checks.rs:103,113`, `has_rationale_before`, `is_secret`) that will drift out of sync as fixes land — this file is not auto-validated against the code it describes, so stale entries can persist after being fixed. Several entries describe known bugs/inversions already present elsewhere in the repo (`.ctxignore` include/exclude swap, hook matcher missing `Edit|Write`, `--dry-run`/`--check` divergence in ctx-scan) — treat this file as a bug tracker as much as a roadmap.

Coupling: this file is itself the subject of one of its own entries ("integrate status more closely into the agent flow"), proposing it be surfaced in prompt injection or replaced by a dedicated tool — so its own format/existence may change based on backlog items it lists.

No code, no functions, no invariants to verify — pure prose/table content. Edits here are additions/removals/reprioritizations of table rows, not logic changes.